{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600532/1930120401/0633.xml":{"full_text":"a CURB SHARES SAG\n7i AS VOLUME GAINS\ni\nMarket Moves Lower in\nAfternoon Following Re\nnewed Selling. r\nBY JOHN A. CRONE.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, December 4.\u2014Despite\nf stubborn resistance, after a weak open\nins, the curb market today moved defi\nnitely lower in the afternoon as volume\n'l Increased.\nElectric Bond Share was down\nnearly a point at the start of the last\nhour and so was Cities Service. The\nlatter is understood to be acquiring\nnatural gas lands in Kentucky and in\nNew York and may be planning enter\nleg the Atlantic seaboard region.\nv Several big blocks of utilities came\nout early in the last hour. American\nSuperpower on a 10,000-share lot at\n12% was ofT and International Utili\nties B on 4,000 shares at 6% was up\nCommonwealth Edison on a sale of 50\nshares fell 2%.\nAmerican Pie Bakeries with a drop\nof 2 points was one of the weakest\nspots in the food list, while among in\nsurance stocks Corron Reynolds pre\nferred lost the same amount. Richfield\nOil preferred ex-warrants rose a point.\nSome of the early soft spots in the\n1 power and light division and their de\ndines follow: Associated Gas <fe Elec\ntrie certificates, off 3%; Bell Telephone\nof Canada, off 1%: Hydro-Electric, off\n1%; National Public Service B, off 4,\nand Pennsylvania Water <Je Power, off\n1% points.\nBabcock Wilcox opened up 3\npoints, proving an exception to the gen\n-1 eral trend in the higher-priced lndus\ntrials. Singer Manufacturing at 348 was\noff 2. Great Atlantic Si Pacific Tea at\nI 176 was off 3%.\nEarly dealings in radios developed a\nA firmer price tendency despite disap\n\u2022T pointing holiday sale reports from the\ntrade. De Forrest, Dubilier Condenser,\n71 Ancturus and other manufacturing\nshares were a trifle higher without,\nhowever, influencing the communication\nissues.\nThe pipe lines bettered. Principal\n4 gains in this group were recorded by\nEureka Pipe, Buckeye Pipe and South\nwest Pennsylvania Pipe. Missourl-\nKansas Pipe, which is a natural gas\n1 carrier, was off fractionally.\nInvestment trusts and trading cor\nporations were dull and Irregular until\nmidday, but shortly thereafter they ap\npeared on the tape with increasing fre\nquency. During this period Insull Utllty\nlost a point. Goldman Sachs was down\n3 about half that amount. Chatham\nf Fheniv was a shade lower and Graymur\nCorporation, which initiated common\nquarterly dividends of 25 cents a share,\nwas slightly higher.\nStromberg-Carlson Telephone in early\nafternoon trading hit a new low for\n1930 by a small decline. Newmont\nmining .was off about a point, but the\nrest of the copper list was virtually un\nchanged. United States Gypsum fell\n1 1% on its initial sale.\nSelling came into convertible pre\nferred shares causing declines of a\npoint or more in Continental Shares,\nInc.; Convertible preferred. Allied In\nterna tic nal investing and similar se\ncurities\nINVESTMENTS IN ORIENT\n$543,694,000 JAN. 1 LAST\nBy the Associated Press.\nDirect American investments in the\nf Orient amounted to $543,694,000 at the\nend of 1929, scattered over six major\nIndustries.\nPetroleum comprises 33.6 per cent of\nthe total, amounting to\nManufacturing is second with $124,475,-\n000, followed in order by selling with\n$56,370,000; rubber. $42,620,000; com\nmunication and transportation. $35,770,-\n000; mining and smelting, $10,077,000,\n4 and miscellaneous, $91,525,000.\nProm these figures it is apparent sell\ning activities lead, as petroleum invest\nments are chiefly in sales organizations.\nApproximately $69,000,000 of the pe\ntroleum total is in Australia and New\nZealand, and $43,000,000 in China. To\nf the petroleum distribution may be add\ned the $56,000,000 representing invest\nments in other sales organizations and,\nwithout allowing for an unknown oor\ntlon of the amount under \u201cmanufac\nturing,\u201d which undoubtedly contains\nsome sales organization, the resultant\nv $239,000,000 is 44 per cent of the Far\nEastern total. After \u201cselling,\u201d the fig\nures show our chief branch plant in\nterest in the Orient to lie in manufac\nturing, followed by other activities; but\nselling and manufacturing combined\nmake about 70 per cent of the total.\nBONDS ON THE CURB\nMARKET\nBates in DOMESTIC BONDS\nU J Aluminum Co 6s \u201962 Voi\u00dfi *103%\n12 Am Cmwlh Pw 6s \u20194O 81 80\u00bb, 80',\n7Amer G E 5* 28 87% 97% 97%\niliS; O 'll\n1 Amer Seating Ss \u20193S. #2% 83% 83\u2019?\n1 Appalach Gas <s '4S 82% 82% 62%\n6 Appalac Gas Ss B '45 88% 67'/* 871:\n\u25a0Hssmsnuitfc hi hi\n-8 Asso O a E 4%s *49 C 71% 71 71\n1 Asso Gas A El 58 \u20186B 77 76% 78%\n5 Asso Gas A El 5s \u2019BB 76*4 75*4 75%\nttifywww a i ss\n1 Bell Tel Can 5s A '55 103% 103*4 103 3 i\n1 Bell Tel Can 6s C 'BO 104% 104% 104%\n4 Bost *Me\u00dfs m\n1 Can Nat R f 7s t 'BS 107% 107% 107*4\n5 Caterpillar Tr 5a \u2019BS #7% 87% 97%\n8 Cent St PAL 5%s '53 82% 82% 82%\n2 Chi Hr cod 5s 2027 72% 72% 72%\n84 Cities Service 5s 50 80 79% 79%\nisfe; ss its r ip 8\u201d\n4 Consum Pow 4%s 'SB 100** 100 100*.\n>4 Cont O At E Ss A 'SB 84 84% 84%\n4 Det C Gas 6s A '47.. 105% 105% 105%\n8 East Util Inv 5s '54 61% 81% 61%\nSEdis \u00bb.Bost 8s A n J! 99% 99% 94%\n2 Elec P A L 5s A 2030 84 84% 84%\n3PI restone C M Ss '4B 81% 81% B**2\n95 Florida PAL 5s '54 83% 83 83\n2 Gen Laundrv 6s '37 47 47 47\n2 Gen Thcat Eq #s '44 19*. 19*. 19*,\n7Georaia Power 5s '67 99 99', os',\ni Grand Trunk B%s '36 107 107 107\nGulf Oil Pa 5s '37. 102 102 10:\u2019\n1 Illin PAL 5%s B '54 99*4 99% 99*4\nI Incinap PAL 5s A '57 99% 99*, 99%\n>4 Insull Utlllt 6s B '4O 90 69*4 89%\n5 In\u00abr Pw Bec 7* R '57 93'/, 93', M%\n2 lowa PAL 4%s 'SB 92 92% 07%\n7 Jer C PAL 5%s A '46 107% 1071, 103%\n|BSBffVV4W?W is., IS\n5La P A L 5i '57 97% 97% 97'/.\n6 Massachu Gas 5s '55 99 99 99\n1 Mass Gas 5%s '4B 107% 102% ioj%\n1 Mead 8s A '4B 80% 90% 90%\ngO Mid West U