2% Trl-Cont Corp t war) 12% 2% 2% 2%\n22% 8% TublzeChatel (8>... 10 6% SV, 6%\u00bb 5%\n36% 13 Ungerlelder F Corp.. 12 23% 24 23% 2t\n42 18 Union Am in vest. 20s 18 18 18 18\n85 17% Un NG of Can t1.60.* 3 17% 17% 17% 17%\n50% 6% Utd Corp (war) 6 8% 8% 8 l\n8% 2% Utd Dry Docks 8 2% *2% 2% 2%\n44 9 Utd Found b 2-35 Sh. 197 9 9% 9 9%\n28% 7% Utd Gas Corpn 96 9% 9% 9 9\n11% 3% Utd Gas (war) 2 3% 3V4 3% 314\n99% 86% Utd Gaa pf (7) 4 67% 87% 87% 87%\n66 24 Utd Lt ft Pow A (1). 46 26% 26% 25% 25%\n99% 66% Utd Lt Pow B (1).. 3 66 66 65 65\n119% 95 Utd Lt ft Pow pf 16). 1 98% 98% 98% 98%\n2% 1% Utd Profit Sharing... 12% 2% 2% 2%\n9% 6V4 Utd Ret Ch pf (3%).. 17% 7% 71/. 7, u\n68% 60 Utd Shoe Mach t 4%. 1 61 61 61 61\n22% 6% U S Elec Pow ww..,, 40 6% 6% 5% 5%\n13% 1 U S Fin Holding 11% yy ]u jy\n26% 4% US Foil (Bt 11. 3 6 6 6 6\n5! U-S Gypsum (t 2.10). 3 40% 40% 40% 40%\n\u2022J* US* *nt Sec Ist (6) 1 41% 41% 41% 41%\n20% 6% U S Lines pf 1 16% 6% 6% 6%\n16 11% US& Over ctfs 28%c 1 14 14 ]4 14\n84 46 US Playing Cardat4) 25s 51 51 61 61\n16% 6% Utd Verde Ext (2)... 26 8 8% 8 8\nHil 1 H% 10% 10%\n29% 17 Util Ind pf (1 1 17% 17% 17 u 17U\n22 5% Utility Equities 4 6% 6% 6% 6%\n6 y\u201d\"'\"\u201d 39 65% 65% 63% 63%\n4% 1% Venezuela Petrol.... 11 1% 1% j% m\n61 21 Vi Walgreen Co 2 21% 21% 21% 21%\n13% 6% Walker (HMD 9 6% 6% 6% 6%\n4% 1% Walker Min (7%c>.. 2 1% 1% f%\n1% Watson (J W) C 0... 2 1% 1% 1% 1%\nol ayn# E Ump 1 6V 6%\n'25 25 Wayne Pump pf 3%. 175 s 24% 24% 24% 24%\n3 2 West Tab ASt (2)... I 27% 27% 27% 27%\n6%. 1% Winter (Benj) 71 \\y t m\n21% 8 Zontte Products <n. 6 9% 9% 9% 9%\nn ,,,irwlnivm?!?!**** 0n ,Mt quarterly or semi-annual\npt. ment. *Ex dividend. tPartly extra iPlut 4% In itock\ndend ytb f b o? ay blt 4 ln e Adjustment divl\nfffigi st \u00b0k C Di\u201e* \u00ae4 *9 \u2022{pc*. hPlut l% in stock.\nnPlu* 2% Ist stock!' kPlus 10% ln tock mPlua in ttock.\nuse their fingers In that distant era for\npicking seeds from the ground or han\ndling small domestic tools, which would\ndevelop the first finger of the hand.\n\nClock Relates Town's History.\nAlmost every town in Europe has a\nwonderful clock, and one which has\nbeen recently placed in Messina Is said\nto be the most wonderful of all. The\nrampant lion la part of the city's\ni coat-of-arms, and it is shown on the\n1 top of the clock. Every day at noon it\nroars, waves a banner and lashes its\ntaU. A bronze cock placed below the\nlion crows a greeting at noon and sun\nset Two arched recesses contain the\nbells upon which the hours are struck\nby figures of Diana and Clarenza, the\nheroines who saved the city from being\nsacked by the French after the Sicilian\nVespers in 1282.\nOn each of the four sides of the\ntower la a luminous dial, 8 feet In di\nameter, upon which are displayed the\nphases of the moon, a perpetual cal\nendar and the movements of the planets\nround the sun. Even Pluto, the latest\ndiscovered planet, finds a place.\nBelow the clock face is a stage, upon\nwhich mechanical figures enact scenes\nappropriate to the great feasts of the\nchurch.\nGreat Northern Bailway.\nNEW YORK, December 4 (IP).\u2014 Ralph\nBudd, president of the Great Northern\nRailway, estimated that the road\u2019s net\nincome for this year will exceed $6 a\nshare. Last year the company earned\n$10.38 a share.\nBANK CLEANINGS.\nNEW YORK, December 4 (Special).\u2014\nNew York bank clearings, today, $969,-\n000,000; a year ago, $1,505,000,000; New\nYork bank balances, today, $140,000,000;\na Vear ago. $310,000,000; New York\nFederal Reserve Bank credits, today,\n$139,000,000; a year ago, $158,000,000.\nKRESS MAY AID\nIN TRADE REVIVAL\nCharacter of Legislation to\nHave Important Effect on\nBusiness World.\n\nBY J. C. BOYLE.\nI\nFully as much anxiety li felt as to\n1 what the present Congress is going to\n1 do to relieve the business minds of both\nemployers and workers as in what Con\ngress may do to relieve unemployment\nand business depression by means of\nlegislation and appropriations.\nEconomists here hold that business\ndepression was never cured by legis)a\ntion and that attempts to legislate the\nproviding and Ailing of Jobs has never\nproven satisfactory, since it is an un\nnatural rather than a natural business\ninfluence. But if Congress, among its\nother relief measures, relieves the minds\nof bankers, investors and business ex\necutives, the latter can be counted on\nto do a little appropriating for expan\n-1 sion on their own account.\ni Employment Volume.\nMen in the closest touch with the\nsituation assert that business slumps are\n1 the result of psychological as much as\n1 actual conditions. President Hoover as\n-1 serted Tuesday that the volume of de\n-1 partment store sales in the last three\nmo\u00dfths only dropped 7 per cent below\nthe corresponding period of 1928, the\nmost prosperous year any country ever\n1 had in world history. The volume of\n1 factory employment for the period, he\nsaid, was 16 per cent below that of\n1928, but the cost of living fell 6 per\ncent, so that the loss was compensated\nto some extent.\n1 On the other hand, bank deposits\nwere 5 per cent higher. Manufactur\n-1 ing production dropped 20 per cent.\nCareful study of those figures offers\nfully as great reassurance as the fact\n1 that President asked Congress\nfor the appropriation of $100,000,000 to\n1 $150,000,000 to increase still further the\nconstruction of public works and build\n-1 ings to aid relief of unemployment and\n1 also will seek authority to make en\nlarged temporary advances of Federal\nhighway aid to the States.\nThe President\u2019s implied assurance\nthat $650,000,000 will be expended in\nthe next six months is hot minimized\np in the slightest as an economic factor,\nbut business men and workers realize\nthat the money for this work will have\nbeen furnished largely by themselves in\nthe form of taxes. They also realize\nthat President Hoover's message car\nried no indication that it would be pos\nsible to continue the temporary in\ncome tax reduction of last year, but\nasserted that extreme care would be\nnecessary to avoid an increase.\nRetail Trade Barometer.\nIt is quite possible that the way In\nwhich Congress handles the problems\nwhich will come before it will aid ma\n-1 terially in reassuring the business\nmind, but what it does regarding bus\nand electric power regulation, railroad\nconsolidation, the consolidation of\nbusiness interests, the present applica\n-1 bility of the Sherman anti-trust law\n1 and taxation, will probably have as\nmuch Influence as any immediate re\n-1 lief measures which it can take.\nIf business can be reassured the\nhuge sums now in the banks can be\nutilized. Only a slight push is needed\nin view of the fact that retail trade\nin the last year has dropped only\naround 7 to 10 per cent. When all is\nsaid retail trade is the real barometer\nof business. It is the first speed gear\ni of business and-high speed can be\nobtained only after the impetus has\ngone from retail to wholesale trade and\ni thence to the manufacure and produc\ni tion of raw materials.\n(Copyright. 1930.)\nGRAIN MARKET\nCHICAGO, December 4 (Special).\u2014\nThe wheat market was irregular today.\nDecember acted firm due to changing of\ni hedges. Later prices reacted in sym\npathy with the break in Winnipeg.\nDecember, old. opened at 76V 4 to 76 3\nMarch, old, 78%; May. old. 79% to 80;\nnew, 80% to 80%. After the first half\nhour December, 75%; March, old, 77%;\nMay, old, 79%; new, 80\nCorn was lower under further pres\nsure from longs because of the reactions\nin wheat. December, old and new\nopened at 7654: March, old, 79>4; new,\n79%: May, old, sl% to 81; new, 81\nAfter the first half hour December, old\nand new, were 76%; March, old, 79%;\nnew, 79%; May, old, 80%; new, 81.\nOats followed other grains. Decem\nber, old, opened 35%; March, old,\n36%; new, 37%; May, old, 38% to 38%;\nnew, 38% to 38%. After the first half\nhour\u2018December, old, 35%; March, old,\n38%; new, 37%; May, old, 37\nNew, 38.\nProvisions were unchanged.\nNEWARK COTTON\nNEW YORK, December 4 (Spe\ncial).\u2014Opening cotton prices today\nwere 3 to 8 points higher. Trading\nwas only moderately active and reflect\ned profit-taking by shorts. New York\nfollowed Liverpool and the movements\nwere almost entirely professional, both\ntrade buying and Southern selling\nbeing noticeable by their absence.\nOpening prices were: December, new,\n10.35, up 5; January, old, 10.44, up 3;\nJanuary, new, 10.47, up 6; March,\n1 10.72, up 6; May, 10.96, up 6; July,\n1 11.12, up .5, and October, 11.33, up 8.\nBusiness Notes\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, December 4.\u2014The toy\nindustry has begun to feel the rush of\ni stores to satisfy the demands upon\ni Santa Claus. Fletcher D. Dodge, sec\nretary of the Toy Manufacturers of the\nUnited States, says consumer toy buy\ning has begun briskly and is producing\na considerable volume of reorders and\nimproved demand for better grade toys.\nHe estimates production of playthings\nthis year will be comparable with 1928,\n1 when the volume was 4 per cent under\nlast year.\nDespite drastic price reductions on\nfloor coverings ranging as high as 30\nper cent buying for January and Febru\n-1 ary delivery has been on a small scale\nthis week. Buyers here for the Spring\nopening said they were satisfied with\nthe new price level, but were not in a\nposition to make heavy commitments\nat this time.\nThe Silk Association reports that the\nconsumption of raw silk during Novem\nber as indicated by deliveries to mills\nwas notably high. The total was 57,333\nbales, only 4,600 bales less than the rec\nord figure set in October.\nSeveral lamp manufacturers, discour\naged by the low prices on low end lamps\nand lamp shades, are reported in the\ntrade to be planning to concentrate next\nrear on better grade goods. The demand\nfor cheap goods has reached a point\nwhere they maintain volume production\nis unprofitable.\nBANKER OFICIALS NAMED.\nBALTIMORE. December 4 (Special).\n\u2014Charles H. Baetjer of J. S. Wilson,\nJr., St Co. was elected chairman of the\nLegislation Committee of the Southeast\nern group of the Investment Bankers\u2019\nAssociation of America for the ensuing\nyear, according to an announcement\nby C. T. Williams, chairman of the\ngroup. Slfford Pearre of the Equit\nable Trust Co., was made chairman of\nthe Membership Committee; Claude W.\nWilhide of Baker. Watts St Co., chair\nman Business Conduct Committee;\nBernard H. Feustman of Frank, Rosen\nburg Co., chairman Entertainment\nCommittee, and John P. Baer of the\nfirm bearing his name, chairman of\nthe Fraudulent Advertising Committee.\nREDUCTION IN CANNED GOODS\nPkOVES CHECK IN PRICE DROP\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nBALTIMORE, December 4. \u2014The\ndrought of last year may prove a bless\ning in disguise to the canner, said\nCharles O. Summers, Jr., former presi\ndent of the Canned Goods Exchange\nof Baltimore and now president of the\nPennsylvania Packers' Association.\nWhile the pack of 1930 is probably\nin the neighborhood of 20 per cent be\nlow the pack of last year, canned goods\nare now selling for less than the cost\nof packing. If the drought had not re\nduced the yield last Summer and thus\nreduced the amount of goods packed,\nthe price now- could be lower than It\nis and the packer would lose more\nmoney.\n\u201cI have not seen figures representing\nthe total pack of tomatoes or the total\nof several other vegetables.\u201d said Mr.\nSummers, \u201cbut the figures for the total\npack of corn given out by the Bureau\nof Foreign and Domestic Commerce show\nthat the pack in 1930 was 15.692,172. as\ncompared with 17,486,744 cases in 1929,\na loss of almost 2.000,000 cans.\n\u201cIn spite of the decreased amount of\ncanned corn, the price is down.\n\u201cThe pack of peas in 1930 in a large\npart of the country was below that of\nGOVERNMENT TO INVESTIGATE\nINCREASE IN BANKRUPTCIES\nf\nBy the Associated Press.\nAlarmed over enormous and growing\nlosses through bankruptcy, the Depart\nment of Justice, through direction of\nPresident Hoover, has set machinery In\nmotion for the most extensive investi\ngation ever attempted of this phase of\nbusiness mortality.\nThe study was prompted by recent\nrevelations in New York which disclosed\nthat total liabilities of more than $5,-\n000,000,000 were Involved in bankrupt\ncies over the last five years, while total\nassets realized were but 11 per cent of\nthese liabilities, and the dividends dis\ntributed to creditors represented leu\nthan 9 cents on the dollar. These losses\nwere deemed sufficient In themselves to\nJustify a national study of th\u00ab bank\nruptcy act as it operates.\nThe program of investigation, an\nnounced by Lloyd K Garrison, special\nassistant to the Attorney Oeneral, has\nbeen prepared in the hope of obtaining\ninformation, suggestions and auistance\nfrom business men, members of the bar\nand others whose work brings them into\ncontact with bankruptcy administration\nin order to obtain a picture of the situa\ntion that will be clear and beyond dis\npute.\nA fertile field which is being drawn\nCASH STOCK BUYING\nHEAVY ON EXCHANGE\nInquiry for Various Issues Con\ntinues\u2014\u201c Under the Market\u2019*\nOrders Large.\nSpecial Dispatch to Tha Star,\nNEW YORK, December 4.\u2014While\nthere is considerable cash buying\ntaking place in the stock market, lt<\nhas naturally decreased in proportion\nto the falling off in total transac\ntions. Brokers report that a good\nmany orders have gone through, with\ntransfers being made to investors in\nodd lots and the big odd-lot houses\ndally buying on balance.\nIt is known that there are a great\nmany orders to buy \u201cunder the mar\nket.\u201d The aggregate of this demand\nis said to be sufficient to constitute a\nvery good cushion and to protect the\nlist in the event of further wave of\nliquidation. Another interesting fea\nture is the amount of exchanging of\nstocks taking place in which tax losses\nare established and the transfer is\nmade from an issue that has lost Its\npopularity in the past year to one that\nnas better prospects for improvement\nwhen the general business situation\nbrightens.*\nDIVIDENDS DECLARED\nNEW YORK, December 4 (;P).\u2014\nltnltr.\nPe- Pay- Hldrs. of\nCompany. Rate.riod. able. record.\nAm Express $1.50 Q Jan. 2 Dec. 19\nAs so Tel ft Tel A ..$1 Q Jan. 1 Dec. 17\nDo. S'* pf .$1.50 Q Jan. 1 Dec. 17\nDo. 7\u2018\u00ab pf $1.75 Q Jan. 1 Dec. 17\nDo. $4 pf $1 Q Jan. 1 Dec. 17\nBandlm Pet 10c M Jan. 20 Dec. 31\nBelding-Cort Ltd .$1.75 Q Feb. 3 Jan. 15\nBritish M A Tr Cor.s6 SA Jan. 2 Dec. 15\nCalamba Bug Est..4oc Q Jan. 2 Dec. 15\nDo 35c Q Jan. 2 Dec. 15\nChi June Ry ft\nUn Stock Yards.s2 28 Q Jan. 2 Dee. 15\nDo. pf $1.50 Q Jan. 1 Dec. 15\nCanad Canners Ltd.2sc Q Jan. 2 Dee. 15\nDo. Ist pf.. ...$1.50 Q Jan. 2 Dec. 15\nDo. conv. pf 25c Q Jan. 2 Dec. 15\nChase Nat Bk INYI.II Q Jan. 2 Dec. 10\nCln ABu Bell T.ll.U's Q Jan. 2 Dec. 19\nCltisens' Water Co ol\nWash Pa pf. ..$1.75 Q Jan. 2 Dec. 20\nClu Peab ft Co pf $1.75 Q Jan. 2 Dec. 19\nCom Credit <N O) .Boc. Q Dec. $1 Dec. 20\nDoeh Die C 77> Pf.B7'/ic Q Jan. 2 Dec. 20\nDo. $7 pf $1.75 Q Jan. 2 Dec. 20\nDunh (J H> C 0.51.50 <3 Jan. 1 Dec. 18\nDo Ist pf $1.50 Q Jan. 1 Dec. 18\nDo. 2d pf $1.25 Q Jan. 1 Dec. 18\nDupl&n Silk pf $2 Q Jan. 2 Dec. 15\nDutn (AC) Lm C.SI 50 Q Dec. 31 Dec. 31\nDo. pf 51.75 Q Dec. 31 Dec. 31\nElm ft Wil RR pf.Sl.Bl SA Jan. 1 Dec. 20\nFirst Am Corp 5c Q Jan. 2 Dec. 18\nFormica Insulation. 50c Q Jan. 1 Dec. 15\nGeneral Mills pf.. 51.50 Q Jan. 2 Dec. 15\nGen Pub Util pf. 51.75 Q Jan. 2 Dec. 15\nIdeal Fin As Cl A.12%c Q Jan. 3 Dec. 15\nDo. pf S 2 Q Jan. 2 Dec. 15\nDo. conv pf 50c Q Jan. 2 Dec. 15\nIntertype Corp 1 pf.S2 Q Jan. 1 Dec. 15\nDo. 2d pf S 3 SA Jan. 1 Dec. 15\nInv C (RI) Ist pf. 51.50 Q Jan. 2 Dec. 20\nMerc Disc pf A...50c Q Jan. 3 Dec. 15\nNew Eng Fire Ins. 25c Q Jan. 2 Dec. 19\nN Y Tel pf 81 62\u2018i Q Jan. 15 Dec 20\nNorth N Y Util pf. 51.75 Q Feb. 1 Jan. 10