BUtlstlcs Co.)\nA J\nF'INANCIALY\n1939. But fanners to Wisconsin and\nMinnesota, where conditions were more\nfavorable, raised great quantities of\npeas and the pack there was extraor\ndinarily large. If those peas became\navailable for the whole country the\nprice would undoubtedly go lower than\nit Is. The people In those States are\ngood bargainers, however, and there\nis no certainty that these peas will be\nmade available for the whole country.\n\"The non-Nordic tomatoes? Before\nthe tariff bill went Into effect the Im\nported tomatoes used to constitute one\nfourth of the total consumption In\nAmerica. I have not seen authoritative\nfigures lately as to Importations. Do\nyou know that In this country we use\n30,000,000 cases of tomatoes each year?\nImportations of a few hundred cases\neach year mean nothing In such a total\nas that.\n\"The canned goods business has under\ngone Its changes In recent years like\neverything else. All orders of canned\ngoods must compete now with green\ngoods shipped here in refrigerator cars\nfrom Florida, from California and even\nfrom the west coast of Mexico. A con\nsiderable quantity of such goods come\nin from the west coast of Mexico.\"\non Is that comprising the referees In\nbankruptcies, numbering about 530, and\nsituated through the country, In locali\nties varying from the smallest towns to\nthe largest cities. Every detail of all\ncircumstances lncdent to bankruptcy,\nincluding the occupation of the bank\nrupt. the causes of his failure and his\nactivities since bankruptcy, will be\ncovered in reports that this group Is\nsubmitting.\nOthers asked to report flndngs are\nthe clerks of the district courts, credit\nadjustment bureaus and other agencies\nhandling out-cf-ourt insolvencies, equity\nreceiverships, bar associations and mem\nbers of the bar and national business\norganizations Interested in the matter.\nAlso, there is much valuable informa\ntion in the files of the Department of\nJustice, Including criminal statistics on\nbankruptcy, reports by examiners and\nby special agents of the Bureau of In\nvestigation concerning apparent crimi\nnal violations assigned to them for in\nvestigation, which will be drawn on In\nthe course of the study. Studies of the\ncauses of commercial failure, made by\nthe Department of Commerce, and re\nports of congressional hearings and de\nbates, will be included in the Investiga\ntion.\nBOND QUOTATIONS\nREACH HUGE SUM\nlimes to Total $1,500,000,000 in\n1930, According to Latest\nEstimate.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, December 4.\u2014State and\nmunicipal bond flotations in 1030 will\naggregate close to $1,500,000,000, ac\ncording to an estimate made by The\nDally Bond Buyer of New York, whose\nsurvey shows that the issues marketed\nduring the 11 months of the current\nyear amount to $1,286,219,500. For the\ncorresponding period of last year the\ntotal was $1,155,864,382.\nDuring the final month of the year\nthe following large Issues are scheduled\nfor sale: Missouri, $5,000,000; South\nCarolina. $10,000,000; Baltimore, Md\u201e\n$4,134,000: Houston, Tex., $3,730,000;\nPhiladelphia. Pa., $15,000,000; Salt\nLake City, Utah, $2,000,000; Providence,\nR. 1., $3,000,000; New Orleans, La., $4,-\n000,000; Louisiana, $15,000,000.\nThe following- table prepared by The\nDaily Bond Buyer of New York com\npares municipal bopd sale totals In\nNovember for the past 10 years:\n41 raos. ending\nNovember. November 30.\n1930 593.784.008 31.286,219.500\n1839 \u00a75,974.063 1.155.864.382\n1838 173,824,090 1.273.678,177\n1927 105.067,010 1.359.866.598\n1926 71.725,702 1.214,790.875\n1925 71.522.706 1.238,429.540\n1924 120,243,926 1,373.088.678\n1923 132,187.398 1.037.820.494\n1922 93.800.366 1.228.058.132\n1921 121,487.608 1.089,623,024\nFOREIGN COLLECTIONS\nSHOWING IMPROVEMENT\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nBALTIMORE, December 4. \u2014Credits\nand collections in many countries have\nbeen greatly improved in the last few\nmonths, due to the revival in several\nindustries and trade, it was reported\nin a bulletin just issued by the Export\nand Import Bureau erf the Baltimore\nAssociation of Commerce.\nThe bulletin quoted a report from\nthe Commercial Intelligence Division,\nBureau of Foreign and Domestic Com\nmerce, United States Department of\nCommerce, as follows:\n\u201cFrom reports received from every\ncommercially important area In the\nworld there is evidence of im\nprovement in the stability of busi\nness. Bankruptcies and protested bills\nhave shown a tendency to be both less\nnumerous and Involving smaller\namounts.\n\u201cWhere unrest occurs in certain\ncountries there has been a tendency\namong merchants to operate conserva\ntively, keeping their stocks reduced and\nmaking their purchases cover only ne\ncessities.\n\u201cStrong, well established firms have\nmade their positions more secure for\nthe return of normal times. They con\ntinue to buy conservatively and meet\ntheir obligations on terms which are\nregularly met.\"\nEARNINGS REPORTED.\nNEW York, December 4 (/P). \u2014Crown\nZellerbach Corporation and subsidiaries\nfor the six months ended .October 31,\nthe first half of Its fiscal year, reported\nnet profit of $1,530,780, against $3,027,-\n628 in the like period of the preceding\nfiscal year.\nCrown Willamette Paper Co. and Pa\ncific Mills for the six months ended\nOctober 31 reported net profit of sl,-\n366,532, against $2,250,209 In the corre\nsponding six months of the previous\nfiscal year.\nA-15\nPIPE LINES REDUCE\nRAILROAD PROFITS\nReports Show Carriers Hav*\nLost Revenue Through New\nTransportation Method.\nBE LEMUEL W. PABTON.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK. December 4.\u2014Back of\nthe uneasiness of railroad management\nand its drive for congressional relief\nlurks a new specter of \u201ctechnological\nunemployment,\" threatening to add a\nbig string of locomotives and freight\ncars to the ranks of the unemployed.\nThe engineers are fixing to add to\ntheir pipe-line repertoire systems which\nwill transport, not oil and gasoline,\nbut cement, pulverised coal and\nother commodities. Experimentally,\ncement already has been moved\nswiftly and satisfactorily by pres\nsure in a pipe line. It Is known\nth *t leading Eastern pipe line is\nmaking these experiments. Maybe this\nbogey is Just a shadow on the wall, so\nfar as long .hauls are concerned, but\nit is typical of the mounting and mul\ntiplying troubles which are prompting\nthe present 8 O 8 to Washington.\nPipe Lines.\nWpe lines are featured heavily la\nthe congressional plea of the railroads.\nThis la understandable, as the following\nroads have taken large cuts in earn\nings due to this competition: Rock\nIsland, Bt. Louis-San Francisco. Mis\nsouri-Kansas-Texas, Atchison, Missouri\nPacific, International Oreat Northern,.\nKansas City Southern, New Orleans.\nTexas 6c Mexico: Chicago, Burlington\nQuincy; Texas 6c Pacific, 8t Louis\nSouthwestern, Southern Pacific and\nColorado 6c Southern,\nThe estimated possible lots per share\nof common stock of these roads, due to\nthe pipe lines, for the first eifht months\nof this year ranges from 40 cento on\nthe Colorado 6c Southern to $3.94 on the\nRock Island. Last year\u2019s earnings per\nshare of the Colorado 6c Southern and\nthe Rock Island were $9.34 and $14.04\nrespectively. Hence it is apparent that,\nto say nothing of the truck competl\ntton, there is possible a considerable\nshrinkage of railroad dividends due to\npipe lines alone.\nunder the commodities clause of the\nInterstate commerce act, the railroads\ncannot transport any article in the\nmanufacture or sale of which they are\nconcerned, directly or indirectly, with\nthe exception of timber. The roads\nwould have Congress extend this restric\ntion to the pipe lines. This would put\nout of business the elaborate network of\npipe lines in which the oil Industry has\ninvested about $400,000,000. It is a safe\nassumption that a distinctly audible\n\u00b0f, \"MProprlstion\u201d will be raised by\nthe oil interests. There ia a prospect of\nheavy firing along the economicfront.\n\"Constructive\u201d Phases.\nRailroad presidents and other spokes\nmen for have emphasized\nthe \"constructive\" phases of railroad\ninsisting that all adjustments\nfurtherance of economic\nneeds. Some of the proposed congres\nsional measures are thus based on the\nforward looking policy phrased by the\nlate E. E. McCormick, vise president of\nthe Southern Pacific, as follows*^*\n\"If you can't lick 'em, join \u2019em.\u201d The\nroads seek amendments of the Panama\nCanal act to allow them to operate\nsteamship lines on the Oreat Lakes\nand on the Pacific and Atlantic Coasts;\nthey ask authority to operate trucks and\nbusses.\nOn the other hand, they ask far a\ntightened check rein on their com\npetitors\u2014license fees for motor vehicles.\nImposing on them a \"fair share\u201d of\nand maintaining\nhighways; the operation of steamshin\nlines under certificates of convenience\nand necessity, and the imposition of\nrommon-carrier restrictions on pipe\nThe present difficulties of the roads\nare the result not only of eoonomlc\nchanges and developments but of the\nu of the#e cul \u201cinatlng forces\nwith the business depression, which has\nprevented the roads from nuUclngada?:\ntattons otherwise possible. For the most\npart the roads are heavily loaded with\nfunded debts. New security issues no\nlonger solve the problem of expansion\nand betterments. While the \u201cpublic\noe damned\u201d' era hai passed and the\nroads are now under more enlightened\nmanagement than ever before, their\ncapital structure and resources are such\nthat their adaptability is vastly lessened\n(Copyright. 1930.)\nCHICAGO LIVE STOCK MARKET\nCHICAGO, December 4 UP) (United\nStates Department of Agriculture).\nHogs, 31,000 head; Including 8,000 di\nrect; rather slow; mostly lOal\u00df higher\nspots, 35 higher early; packing sows,\nstrong to 10 higher; top, s.ss for choice\n160 pounds bulk aU weights, 5.45a8 60;\npacking sows, 7.25a7.55; pigs, 8.35a\u00ab.50.\nLight weight, 160-300 pounds, t.4oa\n8.65; medium weight. 200-250 pounds,\nheav weight, 250-350 pounds.\n8.30a8.55; packing sows, medium and\ngood, 275-500 pounds, 7.25a7.85; slaugh\nter pigs, goad and choice, 100-130\npounds. $.15a8.60.\nCattle. 6.000 head; calves, 3,000; bet-\nter grade fed steers and long yearlings\nstrong to 35 higher; supply scarce; toD\nyearlings, 13.15; trade active on au\ngrades weighty bullocks selling 11.78\ndown to 10.50; some scaling 1,643\npounds at 11.50;, other classes steady to\ngrades, light mixed\nend heifer yearlings, continuing dull\nat decline. Slaughter cattle and verniers:\nSteers, good and choice, 600-900\npounds. 10.25a13.75; 900-1,100 pounds.\n10.25a13.75; 1,100-1,300 pounds, 9.75a\n13.50; 1,300-1,500 pounds, 9.75a13.00;\ncommon and medium, 600-1,300 pounds\n6.50a10.25. Heifers, good and choice\u2019,\n550-850 pounds, 8.50a12.50; common\nand medium. 5.00a9.00. Cows, good and\nchoice, 5.25a7.25; common and medium\n3.75a5.25; low cutter and cutter, 3.00a\n4.00. Bulls (yearlings excluded), good\nand choice (beef), 5.25a6.50; cutter to\nmedluin, 4.00a5.75. Vealers (milk fed),\ngood and choice. B.SOall.SO; medium,\n6.50a8.50; cull and common. 5.0056.50.\nStocker and feeder cattle: Steers, good\nand choice, 500-1,050 pounds, 7 00a9 00*\ncommon and medium, 5.50a7.00\nSheep\u2014Receipts. 11,000 head; fat\nlambs strong to 25 higher; sheep and\nfeeders stead* early bulk iambs, s.ooa\n8.35 to packers; several loads 8.60a8.78\nto shippers snd city butchers. Lambs.\n90 pounds down, good and choice, 7.75a\n8.85; medium, 6.25a7.75; all weights\ncommon, 5.00a6.25. Ewes, 90-180 pounds!\nmedium to choice. 3.00a5.78; all weights\ncull and common, 1.00a2.50. Feeding\nl^bS'J 0 75 pounds, good and choice,\n6.75a7.50.\nNEW TRADE STATISTICS.\nBy the Associated Press.\nIn a recent address, E. B. George\nchief of the Market Service Division of\nthe Department of Commerce, said the\ndistribution census statistics, to be nub-\nUshed shortly, will give manufacturers,\nsales managers and advertisers a solid\nfoundation upon which to build es\ntimates of marketing possibilities by\nproviding a new. basis of actual facto\nfor the determination of sales territories\nand advertising quotas.\nMr. George said the statistics can be\nadapted to the efforts of merchandising\nfirms to' reduce costs by eliminating\naimless and expensive sales methods.\nCHICAGO DAIRY MARKET.\nCHICAGO, December 4 UP).\u2014Butter\u2014\n-4,767 tubs; firm; creamery extras. 33 K:\nstandards. 32; extra firsts, 31>Aa32V4;\nfirsts, 29a30>/ a seconds, 265a37H.\nEggs\u20142,973 crates; unsettled; extra\nfirsts, 39; fresh graded firsts, 37; fresh\ncurrent receipts, 38; ordinary current\nreceipts, 21a33; refrigerator firsts, lsa\n19 V 4; refrigerator extras, 20fes31.\nv/ \"l","height":"25416","width":"19701"}}
